Given the accumulated evidence that ME/CFS is a systemic biological disease—not a syndrome, not mere fatigue, and not a psychological condition—this document proposes a new designation that more accurately reflects the core pathology: *dysergopoiesis*. This is a terminological proposal by the present authors; it has not been reviewed or adopted by the ME/CFS research community or any nosological authority.

The term is constructed from three Greek roots:

    / *_dys-_ (δυσ-)*: impaired, disordered—the standard medical prefix indicating dysfunction, as in dys\-lexia, dys\-pnea, dys\-tonia.
    / *_ergo-_ (ἔργον)*: work, energy—the root found in _erg_ (the unit of energy), _ergonomics_, and _synergy_.
    / *_-poiesis_ (ποίησις)*: making, production—the suffix used throughout hematology and cell biology: _hematopoiesis_ (blood cell production), _erythropoiesis_ (red blood cell production), _leukopoiesis_ (white blood cell production).

 Dysergopoiesis therefore means, literally, *impaired energy production*. As a Greek scientific coinage, the term is essentially identical across languages—just as _dyslexia_, _anemia_, and _hematopoiesis_ require no translation:

