==== Why "Dysergopoiesis"?

*It names the central pathological process, not a symptom.*
A central biological finding in ME/CFS is not "fatigue" but a measurable impairment of the body's ability to produce and deliver usable energy. The 2024 NIH deep phenotyping study documented depleted catecholamines in cerebrospinal fluid, exhausted T-cell populations unable to switch metabolic modes, dysfunctional B-cell maturation, and decreased temporoparietal junction activity @walitt2024deep. Mitochondrial oxidative phosphorylation is compromised (see Chapter @ch:energy-metabolism), immune cells cannot perform the glycolysis-to-OXPHOS transition required for sustained function (see Chapter @ch:immune-dysfunction), and autonomic regulation of energy distribution fails under challenge (see Chapter @ch:cardiovascular). Whether the primary defect is cellular energy _production_ per se or energy _coordination and allocation_ — the impaired ability to mobilise energy on demand despite potentially intact resting production (see Chapter @ch:energy-metabolism) — remains an open question. The term _dysergopoiesis_ is intended broadly: _ergon_ (work, energy) and _poiesis_ (making, producing) encompass the entire process by which the body generates and makes energy available for use, including demand-responsive mobilisation. In this reading, dysergopoiesis names the failure of the energy supply system as a whole — whether the bottleneck is mitochondrial capacity, substrate delivery, or the coordination signals that mobilise reserves in response to demand.

*It names the common denominator, not a contested cause.*
One of the deepest problems in ME/CFS nosology is that different patients may arrive at the same clinical picture through different upstream mechanisms: post-infectious mitochondrial damage, autoantibodies targeting metabolic or vascular receptors, autonomic failure impairing substrate delivery, connective tissue disorders compromising perfusion, or mast cell–mediated metabolic disruption. The resulting debates about _which_ mechanism is primary have stalled both naming and research for decades. Dysergopoiesis resolves this by naming the hypothesised _convergent endpoint_ — the shared downstream failure in energy supply — rather than any single upstream cause. This is analogous to _anemia_, which names the functional deficit (insufficient oxygen-carrying capacity) regardless of whether the cause is iron deficiency, hemolysis, B12 deficiency, chronic disease, or bone marrow failure. No one argues that "anemia" is a bad name because it has multiple etiologies; the etiologies become qualifiers (_iron-deficiency anemia_, _hemolytic anemia_). A critical difference, however, is that anemia has a universally agreed laboratory correlate (haemoglobin concentration); a comparable unified biomarker for dysergopoiesis does not yet exist, though candidates include two-day CPET performance decline, metabolomic profiles @Naviaux2016metabolic, and lactate kinetics. Until such a biomarker is validated, the convergence claim remains a working hypothesis rather than an established fact.

*It is consistent with post-exertional malaise.*
The cardinal symptom of ME/CFS — the pathological worsening that follows even minimal exertion — is consistent with impaired energy supply: if the body cannot produce or mobilise energy adequately, demand-exceeding activity should produce a deficit. The characteristic 12–48-hour delay and immune-activation component of PEM suggest this is not simple fuel depletion but involves a dysregulated recovery response (see Chapter @ch:energy-metabolism), which the broad reading of dysergopoiesis (encompassing mobilisation and recovery, not only ATP synthesis) is intended to capture.

*It follows established medical word formation.*
The _dys- + [process] + -poiesis_ pattern is standard in medicine. Just as _dyserythropoiesis_ means impaired red blood cell production and _dyshematopoiesis_ means impaired blood cell production, _dysergopoiesis_ means impaired energy production. Any physician who encounters the term can parse it immediately.

==== Advantages Over Existing Nomenclature

    - *No trivialization*: "Dysergopoiesis" cannot be confused with ordinary tiredness. No one says "I have a bit of dysergopoiesis" after a long day at work.
    - *Mechanism-centered*: The name points to a central pathological process (impaired energy supply) rather than to a single symptom (fatigue) or to an undemonstrated neurological claim (encephalomyelitis).
    - *Signals biological investigation*: A name centred on impaired energy supply signals to clinicians and researchers that the disease has a biological mechanism requiring investigation — a framing that the term "chronic fatigue" actively suppresses. This is a communication advantage, not a claim that the name itself determines treatment.
    - *Neutral with respect to etiology*: The name does not presuppose a specific trigger (viral, autoimmune, genetic). It describes _what is broken_ regardless of _why_, making it applicable across all patient subgroups (see the anemia analogy above).
    - *Natural subtype taxonomy*: Because dysergopoiesis names the hypothesised common endpoint, it naturally accommodates etiological subtypes as qualifiers — _post-infectious dysergopoiesis_, _autoimmune dysergopoiesis_, _hypermobility-associated dysergopoiesis_ — mirroring how anemia accommodates iron-deficiency, hemolytic, and aplastic subtypes. Note that no validated diagnostic criteria currently exist for assigning individual patients to these subtypes; the taxonomy is a framework for future precision medicine, not a classification instrument ready for clinical use today.
    - *No psychogenic connotation*: The Greek medical construction carries inherent biological authority. No component of the word can be misread as implying volition, preference, or psychological causation.
    - *Universally intelligible*: Being a Greek scientific coinage, the term requires no translation—it is the same word in every language, just as _dyslexia_ is. This eliminates the problem of divergent national names (ME in the UK, CFS in the US, SFC in France) that has fragmented the patient community and confused the research literature.
    - *Shorter and more pronounceable than "myalgic encephalomyelitis"*: At six syllables versus eleven, _dysergopoiesis_ is more compact and follows familiar phonetic patterns (_dys-er-go-poi-e-sis_). Patients can learn, spell, and pronounce it—unlike "encephalomyelitis," which most patients cannot spell and most physicians cannot pronounce correctly on first encounter.

==== Comparison with Previous Renaming Attempts

The 2015 Institute of Medicine proposal "Systemic Exertion Intolerance Disease" (SEID) @IOM2015 failed to gain widespread adoption. SEID was criticised on multiple grounds: the word "intolerance" was perceived by patients as connoting psychological aversion rather than physiological incapacity; the name still centred on a _symptom_ (intolerance to exertion) rather than on an underlying pathology; and the acronym lacked recognition. The IOM committee had deliberately chosen a symptom-based name to avoid premature mechanistic commitment — a methodologically cautious position (see @lim:premature-naming-risk below).

Dysergopoiesis differs fundamentally: it names the _process that fails_ (energy supply), not the _symptom that results_ (exertion intolerance or fatigue). This distinction mirrors _dyserythropoiesis_, which names the failed process (red blood cell production) rather than its clinical consequence (anemia), or _congestive heart failure_, which names the functional deficit (impaired cardiac output leading to fluid congestion) rather than any single upstream cause (ischemia, valvular disease, cardiomyopathy).

Moreover, dysergopoiesis offers a framework for the long-standing debate over whether ME/CFS is one disease with variable presentation or several diseases sharing a symptom profile. If the convergent-endpoint hypothesis holds, both views are accommodated: it is one condition (impaired energy supply is the shared pathology), but it may have multiple distinct etiologies, each of which becomes a subtype. Medicine routinely classifies conditions this way: heart failure has ischaemic, valvular, and cardiomyopathic subtypes. The unifying name captures the hypothesised shared pathology while subtypes, once validated, would guide targeted treatment. If, however, future research demonstrates that some ME/CFS subtypes have no measurable energy supply deficit — for instance, if a purely autonomic or purely immune-mediated subgroup is identified with normal bioenergetics — this would weaken the case for dysergopoiesis as a universal label and might favour a more general term.
